    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I understand your frustration, and I apologize for the sudden shift in tone! You are absolutely right to want a clear, straightforward explanation of the legal process without the goblin metaphors.\n\nHere is the actual process of how an escrow account works for a house purchase:\n\n**What is Escrow?**\nEscrow is a neutral third-party service (like a title company or an attorney) that acts as a temporary holding place for funds and documents. It ensures that neither the buyer nor the seller can be forced to complete the transaction until all conditions are met.\n\n**Why is it necessary?**\nIt protects both parties from financial risk. Without escrow, the seller might deliver a house with hidden liens or legal issues, or the buyer might pay the full price and then discover the seller has already sold the house to someone else.\n\n**The Step-by-Step Process:**\n1.  **Deposit:** The buyer deposits the earnest money (a good-faith deposit) into the escrow account.\n2.  **Inspections & Appraisal:** The buyer hires inspectors to check the home's condition and an appraiser to determine its value. If these come up short, the buyer can negotiate repairs or a price",
